Is that example in the screenshot a good one?<p>This works fine in a Content Scratchpad of nightly Firefox for me:<p><pre><code>  // See also
  // https://github.com/richgilbank/ES6-Repl-Chrome-Extension/issues/12
  function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
  }
  let nums = [5, 4];
  console.log(&quot;foobar&quot; + add(...nums));</code></pre>

Unless I&#x27;m missing something, enums are closed, thus overlap with sum types for the use-cases. Subclasses are an implementation detail in this context. Here is an example that uses subclasses to implement generalized enums, aka sum types:<p><pre><code>  enum List {
    Cons(head, tail) {...}
    Nil {...}

    int length() {
      switch (this) {
        case Cons(head, tail): return 1 + length(tail) 
        case Nil: return 0
      }
    }
  }
</code></pre>
Mind you, this is syntactic sugar and you can do it by hand with enums + sublcasses. But the whole point of clean languages is to remove unnecessary boilerplate :)

